  "doc_id": "22970",
  "text": "MC2R, activated by ACTH, is involved in androgen and steriodogenic enzyme synthesis. It is normally expressed in the adrenal gland cortex and epidermis as well as in basal cell carcinoma tissue and cultured melanocytes. As with other GPCRs, MC2R binding ACTH activates adenylyl cyclase with subsequent production of cAMP. Cyclic AMP can then directly activate or interact with various proteins such as ionchannels, transcription factors, guanine nucleotide exchange factors, and protein kinases such as PKA. PKA and cAMP play critical roles in the progression and differentiation of prostate carcinogenesis [CITATION_1] . Activation of MC2R can also result in phosphorylation of MAPK and the MC2R accessory protein isoform β (MRAP-β) in cells stably expressing MC2R [CITATION_2] . Similarly, ectopic production of ACTH, the putative ligand for MC2R, has been reported in cases of prostate carcinoma associated with Cushing's syndrome [CITATION_3] .",
